http://www.who.int/csr/don/8-february-2016-gbs-france-martinique/en/

South America
---
Brazil:
- Goiana, Pernambuco state. 15 Feb 2016. (susp.) 40 000 cases, reportedly the highest incidence in Brazil; microcephalic infants 27; city health emergency declared.
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3447572/The-world-s-infected-town-Inside-tiny-Brazilian-death-zone-500-DAY-struck-deadly-Zika-virus-police-fight-filthy-hoarders-spread-disease.html

- Espirito Santo State. 5 Feb 2016. (susp) 1526 cases, (conf) 13 cases.
http://g1.globo.com/espirito-santo/noticia/2016/02/professora-morre-de-dengue-hemorragica-em-cachoeiro-es.html [in Portuguese]

[A 4 Feb 2016 report stated that a preliminary study by the University of Haifa and the European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) found a linkage between the exceptionally hot and dry winter and spring recently experienced in north east Brazil and the outbreak of the Zika virus. Hot temperatures may accelerate development of the vector mosquito, and dry conditions lead to water storage, providing vector mosquito habitats (http://www.newswise.com/articles/findings-of-a-preliminary-study-at-university-of-haifa-find-correlation-between-exceptionally-hot-and-dry-winter-in-northeast-brazil-and-outbreak-of-the-zika-virus). - Mod.TY]

- Zika infection deaths. 11 Feb 2016. (conf) 3rd death, as 20 year old woman began coughing up blood died after a 12-day hospitalization. One of the Zika patients who died in Brazil last year [2015] also had lupus. The other was a 16 year old girl who had no serious underlying health problems.
https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/brazil-says-a-third-adult-has-died-of-zika/2016/02/11/100e669a-d0d3-11e5-90d3-34c2c42653ac_story.html?hpid=hp_hp-cards_hp-card-world%3Ahomepage%2Fcard

- microcephaly deaths. 13 Feb 2016. (reported) 24 infants died of microcephaly with 59 more deaths under investigation.
http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/suspected-zika-lined-microcephaly-cases-rise-to-5-079-in-brazil-116021300459_1.html

[A 13 Feb 2016 report quotes the Brazil Minister of Health saying: "We are absolutely sure of the causal relationship between microcephaly and Zika," he said, adding that government researchers were unanimous in their assessment: "It has nothing to do with the environment, nothing to do with race, nothing to do with gender." See the article below at the end of this update, which disputes this statement. (http://www.scmp.com/news/world/article/1912516/brazilian-health-minister-absolutely-sure-connection-between-zika-virus).

A 14 Feb 2016 report stated that Zika virus infections as the etiology of microcephaly has recently been challenged by a group of Argentine physicians. The group suspects that the Zika virus is not to blame for the rise in microcephaly cases but that a toxic larvicide (pyriproxifen) introduced into Brazil's water supplies for mosquito control may be the real culprit. (http://www.techtimes.com/articles/133548/20160214/monsanto-larvicide-not-zika-virus-true-cause-of-brazils-microcephaly-outbreak-doctors.htm). This is a speculative association, not proven causation. The Brazil Ministry of Health stated that use of pyriproxifen and microcephaly has no scientific basis. The ministry indicates that it is important to note that some localities that do not use pyriproxifen also have microcephaly cases. (http://portalsaude.saude.gov.br/index.php/cidadao/principal/agencia-saude/22161-esclarecimento-sobre-o-uso-do-larvicida-pyriproxifen in Portuguese
If there is scientific evidence of this toxicant causing microcephaly, ProMED-mail would be interested in receiving it. - Mod.TY]

